comments.undefined: The Ontology for Preclinical Trials in Radiation Oncology (PTRO), is a domain-specific ontology designed to integrate SEND-standardized preclinical data using semantic web technologies. PTRO incorporates the Semantic Types Ontology (STY) as a framework for broad concept categorization.

definition.value: One of the three domains of life (the others being Bacteria and Archaea), also called Eukarya. These are organisms whose cells are enclosed in membranes and possess a nucleus. They comprise almost all multicellular and many unicellular organisms, and are traditionally divided into groups (sometimes called kingdoms) including Animals, Plants, Fungi, various Algae, and other taxa that were previously part of the old kingdom Protista.

A 128 bit identifier. Depending on the mechanism used to generate it, it is either guaranteed to be different from all other UUIDs/GUIDs generated until 3400 AD or extremely likely to be different. Its relatively small size lends itself well to sorting, ordering, and hashing of all sorts, storing in databases, simple allocation, and ease of programming in general.
A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to comments.
One or more characters used to identify, name, or characterize the nature, properties, or contents of a thing.
Any of numerous species of small rodents belonging to the genus Mus and various related genera of the family Muridae.

definition.value: An identifier which is used to uniquely identify an animal in a certain context (cohort, hospital, trial). Can be a pseudonym.
A process or state which occurs naturally or as a result of an activity.

A member of one of the three domains of life, formerly called Archaebacteria under the taxon Bacteria, but now considered separate and distinct. Archaea are characterized by: 1) the presence of characteristic tRNAs and ribosomal RNAs; 2) the absence of peptidoglycan cell walls; 3) the presence of ether-linked lipids built from branched-chain subunits; and 4) their occurrence in unusual habitats. While archaea resemble bacteria in morphology and genomic organization, they resemble eukarya in their method of genomic replication.
A broad type for grouping abstract entities or concepts.
A broad type for grouping physical and conceptual entities.
An object perceptible to the sense of vision or touch.
A sequence of characters used to identify a treatment session.

definition.value: A set of characters used as a code that is unique in the context or the system for which it is created. It serves as a means of identification and reference (often instead of a name) for an entity, person, thing, function, procedure, activity, variable, or body of data.
A sequence of characters used to identify laboratory records.

definition.value: A broad type for grouping activities, processes and states.
An operation or series of operations that an organism or machine carries out or participates in.
A conceptual entity resulting from human endeavor. Concepts assigned to this type generally refer to information created by humans for some purpose.

A eukaryotic organism characterized by the absence of chlorophyll and the presence of a rigid cell wall. Included here are both slime molds and true fungi such as yeasts, molds, mildews, and mushrooms.

An organism consisting of a core of a single nucleic acid enclosed in a protective coat of protein. A virus may replicate only inside a host living cell. A virus exhibits some but not all of the usual characteristics of living things.
A small, typically one-celled, prokaryotic micro-organism.
An organism with eukaryotic cells, and lacking stiff cell walls, plastids and photosynthetic pigments.
An area of knowledge considered as a discrete unit for some purpose.
Generally, a living individual, including all plants and animals.

An organism having cellulose cell walls, growing by synthesis of inorganic substances, generally distinguished by the presence of chlorophyll, and lacking the power of locomotion. Plant parts are included here as well.
A vertebrate having a constant body temperature and characterized by the presence of hair, mammary glands and sweat glands.
A sequence of characters used to identify procedure records.

definition.value: An animal which has a spinal column.
A cold-blooded, smooth-skinned vertebrate which characteristically hatches as an aquatic larva, breathing by gills. When mature, the amphibian breathes with lungs.
A vertebrate having a constant body temperature and characterized by the presence of feathers.

A cold-blooded aquatic vertebrate characterized by fins and breathing by gills. Included here are fishes having either a bony skeleton, such as a perch, or a cartilaginous skeleton, such as a shark, or those lacking a jaw, such as a lamprey or hagfish.
A subject domain utilized for the submission of information encompassing and representing data, vocabulary or records related to clinical observations.
A cold-blooded vertebrate having an external covering of scales or horny plates. Reptiles breathe by means of lungs and are generally egg-laying.

End date/time of the procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format.
Study day of start of procedure expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.
Short name for ARM (may be up to 20 characters) used for sorting and programming. Should be populated when Arms have been defined in the TA domain.
Descriptive name given to a specific Trial Arm (e.g., Low Dose, Mid Dose, 10 mg/kg/day dose, Third Arm) to which the subject was assigned.
Short name of a specific Trial Set to which the subject was assigned, as defined by the sponsor. Maximum of 8 characters. This represents the Trial Set for which parameters are being submitted.
Study day of end of procedure expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.
Collected duration of a procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.
A unique alphanumeric identifier assigned to a project to ensure its distinct identification within a given system, organization, or dataset.

comment.undefined: This attribute is not part of the CDISC standard; it was defined by our DKFZ working group (E220).

definition.value: Used when a specific procedure is pre-specified on a CRF. Values should be "Y" or null.
Start date/time of the procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format.
Anatomical location of a procedure.
Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality.
Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality.
Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution, which means arrangement of, apportioning of.
Used to record whether a prespecified procedure occurred when information about the occurrence of a specific procedure is solicited.
Amount of PRTRT administered. Not populated when PRDOSTXT is populated.
Units for PRDOSE, PRDOSTOT, or PRDOSTXT.
Usually expressed as the number of doses given per a specific interval.
Subject (i.e., Animal) identifier used within the study.
Route of administration for EXTRT. Examples: ORAL GAVAGE, DERMAL, INTRAVENOUS.
Describes vehicle used for treatment. Example: SALINE.
Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.
Study day of body weight collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.

Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in DDTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in DDTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). DDTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores.
Name of the treatment, as defined by the protocol.

Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in BWTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in BWTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). BWTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores.
Long name for BWTESTCD. The value in BWTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters.
Unique identifier for a study.
Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.
Used to further categorize a group of clinical observations within a category. For example "Whole Body Appearance" and "Sensory Organ Appearance" may be subcategories within Clinical Signs.
May be derived (RFSTDTC - BRTHDTC), but BRTHDTC may not be available in all cases. Age may also be collected.
Units associated with AGE and AGETXT.
Used to define a category of the clinical observation.

Study day of observation, in integer days. For measurements related to a continuous evaluation interval, CLDY can be used to indicate start day of that interval. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.
Body system or organ class associated with the measurement performed.
Used to categorize the result of a finding post collection. Examples: Color or Facial.
Used to indicate examination not done or result is missing. Should be null if a result exists in CLORRES.
Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Example: TOX TECHNICIAN, OPHTHALMOLOGIST, VETERINARIAN.
Long name for DDTESTCD. The value in DDTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters.
Used to categorize the result of a finding. Examples: TREATMENT RELATED, NONTREATMENT RELATED, UNDETERMINED, ACCIDENTAL, etc.
Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Examples: TOX PATHOLOGIST, PEER REVIEW, SPONSOR, VETERINARIAN.
Study day of subject disposition, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.

Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in CLTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in CLTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). CLTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores.
Long name for CLTESTCD. The value in CLTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters.
Amount of treatment administered.
Units for EXDOSE or EXDOSTXT. Examples: ng, mg, or mg/kg.

The amount (volume or weight) of the treatment compound plus vehicle administered in a single dose. This is not to be confused with EXDOSE. EXDOSE refers to the amount of test material administered to the subject.
Units for EXVAMT (per dose administration).
Session identifier used within the EX template.
Study day when administration of the treatment ended, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.
Duration and unit of time for a continuous treatment. This may be used to denote the length of an infusion (e.g., PT10M to indicate 10 minutes).
Two-character abbreviation for the domain.

Used when the age is a range and the exact birthdate is not known. This variable is a character field for the purposes of defining age ranges, e.g., if the information available for the age of the subject is 6-8 and AGEU is WEEKS. Populate only when BRTHDTC or AGE is not specified. The format for AGETXT is "number-number" (e.g., 6-8).
Study day when administration of the treatment began, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.
The sex of the subject.

Used to identify the vendor-supplied strain, substrain, or breed designation for the test system under study. It may combine the background strain, substrain, and associated genetic modifications as supplied by the vendor (e.g., C57BL/6, A/J, B6.129-Pparg<tm2Rev>/J, FISCHER 344, SPRAGUE-DAWLEY IGS, WISTAR Kyoto, BEAGLE, CYNOMOLGUS, and CHIMPANZEE). The SEND Controlled Terminology codelist consists of commonly used wild type strains. It is extensible to accommodate strains not listed and genetically modified substrains. If this variable is excluded in the DM domain, the information must be present at a higher level (either Trial Sets or Trial Summary). Country of origin for non-human primates should not go into STRAIN. In general, details related to coat color (e.g., White and Red designations for New Zealand Rabbits) should not go into STRAIN.
The unit for the original result. The unit of the original result should be mapped to a synonymous unit on the Controlled Terminology list.

definition.value: Relation between an activity and  an entity,  at which the entity participates in some way in the activity or process.
This property links a 'Subject Unique Identifie'r  to a 'Laboratory Record Identifier'
This property links a 'Subject Unique Identifier'  to a 'Treatment Session Identifier'
Study day of specimen collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.
Study day of the end of specimen collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.
Nominal study day used for grouping records for specimen collections that may occur on different days into a single reported study day. Should be an integer.
A label for a given value of LBNOMDY as presented in the study report. Examples: Week 4, Day 28, Terminal Sac.
A baseline indicator may be used to calculate differences or changes from baseline. Value should be Y or null. The baseline flag is sponsor defined.
Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor that provided the test results.

Defines the specific anatomical or biological region of a tissue, organ specimen, or the region from which the specimen was obtained, such as a section or part of what is defined in the LBSPEC variable. If the anatomical region is not included in the specimen description LBSPEC, it may be included in this variable. This field can be a combination of terms where needed. This field can be null if not applicable. Examples: CORTEX, MEDULLA, MUCOSA, SEROSA, ISLET, ZONA FASICULATA, ZONA RETICULARIS, CRANIAL, MEDIAN, ACCESSORY, SPINAL, LUMBAR, FRONTAL.
Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Examples: HEMOLYZED, ICTERIC, LIPEMIC
Describes the usability of the specimen for the test. Should be N if the specimen is not usable; otherwise it should be null.

Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in LBTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in LBTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). LBTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: ALT, LDH.
Long name for LBTESTCD. The value in LBTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: Alanine Aminotransferase, Lactate Dehydrogenase.
Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.
The unit for the original result. The unit of the original result should be mapped to a synonymous unit on the Controlled Terminology (http://www.cdisc.org/terminology) list.
Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the portion or totality, which means arrangement of, or apportioning of. Examples: ENTIRE, SINGLE, SEGMENT, MANY.
Method of the test or examination. Examples: EIA (Enzyme Immunoassay), ELECTROPHORESIS, DIPSTICK

Standardized or dictionary-derived name of PRTRT. If the codelist "PROCEDUR" is not used, the sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms in the external codelist element in the Define-XML document. If an intervention term does not have a decode value, then PRDECOD will be null.
Used to define a category of procedure values.
Used to define a further categorization of PRCAT values.
The text of the comment. Text over 200 characters can be added to additional columns COVAL1-COVALn. See Assumption 4 in Section 5.2.1.1.
Used to describe the originator of the comment. Examples: TECHNICIAN, STUDY DIRECTOR, VET.

Date/Time of the comment, in ISO 8601 format. May be null if this is a child record of another domain or if the comment date was not collected. In all other cases, this represents the date/time of the comment in ISO 8601 format.

Study day of the comment, in integer days. May be null if this is a child record of another domain or if the comment date was not collected. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.
Name of procedure performed, either preprinted or collected on a CRF.

Variable in the parent dataset that identifies the record(s) to which the comment applies, which is contained in IDVAR. Examples: BWSEQ or CLGRPID. Used only when individual comments are related to domain records.
Value of identifying variable of the parent record(s). Used only when individual comments are related to domain records. Cannot be populated if IDVAR is null.
This property links a 'Subject Unique Identifier'  to a 'Procedure Identifier'
A label for a given value of BWNOMDY as presented in the study report. Examples: "Week 4," "Day 28," "Terminal Sac".
This property links a 'Subject Unique Identifie'r  to a 'Body Weigh Identifier'
